titlestmt.titleproper: Guide to the Robert Hebb Records
titlestmt.author: Aaron Greene

profiledesc.creation: Finding aid created with EADitor by Aaron Greene.

did.abstract: This collection contains folders of the administrative materials of Robert Hebb, Director of Horticulture at the Cary Arboretum from 1974 to 1984.

accessrestrict.p: This collection is open to researchers by appointment only.

bioghist.p: Robert Hebb received a degree in ornamental horticulture from the University of Rhode Island in 1965, after which he worked as a student gardener at the Royal Botanical Gardens, Kew in England until 1968. From 1968 to 1974, Hebb worked at the Arnold Arboretum of Harvard University, where he was the Assistant Horticulturist. He became the Director of Horticulture at the Cary Arboretum in 1974, when the arboretum was under the management of the New York Botanical Garden.

scopecontent.p: This collection consists largely of memoranda, correspondence, and inventories of plant material. Some landscape and building plans, photographs, and miscellaneous newspaper articles and pamphlets are also included. The correspondence is mostly communication with administrators and employees about operations and finances. A large amount of correspondence with arboreta, other horticulturists, and garden clubs about plant inventories, seed exchange, and events is also present. The collection is divided into 10 series with 510 folders, a number of which contain only one or two items. Materials such as field books and survey sheets that are not in folders can be found in Series 5. Additional folders originally in the collection were given to the New York Botanical Garden.

userestrict.p: The materials in this collection are protected by copyright.

scopecontent.p: This series contains miscellaneous memoranda, correspondence, and other administrative materials.

This series contains plant lists, correspondence, and memoranda pertaining to plant acquisitions, donations, and the distribution of surplus plant material. Additional folders originally in this series were given to the New York Botanical Garden.

This series contains field books, survey sheets, and grid locations from inventories of plant material at the Cary Arboretum. The field books and survey sheets deal with material accessioned in the winter of 1976-1977, and are accompanied by an instruction manual developed by Marshall & Stevens, Inc. for analyzing, classifying, and creating a standardized inventory of major plant material. The grid locations detail inventories of tree collections taken between 1977 and 1979.

scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, correspondence, and field survey questionnaires from a survey of container-grown plants in urban spaces conducted in 1975. The study was financed by a grant from the National Endowment for the Arts with the goal of developing a manual of information about container planting.
